{"response_text": "The analysis of cumulative postpartum female mortality reveals a distinct biphasic trajectory characterized by an initial surge in predation followed by a prolonged plateau. During the initial phase (ticks 0 to 231), the accumulation rate is steep (slope 0.213, p < 0.001), indicating an aggressive early harvesting period. Subsequent phases show a rapid deceleration in the rate of new kills. Between ticks 464 and 695, the slope decreases to 0.059, and by the window spanning ticks 1392 to 1623, the upward trend becomes statistically insignificant (p = 0.066), signaling a functional halt in new mortalities. 

The aggregate mean of 40 simulation runs indicates a local maximum in the mean series at tick 1826, reaching a cumulative count of 119.0000 individuals removed. By the conclusion of the observation window at tick 2312, the mean stabilizes near 117.0000. Distinct inflection points identified at indices 245, 475, and 625 mark transitions in hunting efficiency. A dominant oscillation period of 63.00 ticks is observed, likely linked to the environmental seasonality parameter (set at 0.8).

For decision makers, these dynamics highlight a critical window of vulnerability for the herd's reproductive capacity within the first 1400 ticks. The saturation point around 117 cumulative losses out of an initial prey population of 250 suggests that the targetable demographic (postpartum females) is either functionally depleted or has adapted to avoid further predation after the initial pulse. This implies that while human foragers exert high initial pressure, the system naturally limits cumulative mortality, potentially due to prey behavior or resource distribution limits."}

